[[Image:Simone Martini 046.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Saint Elisabeth of Hungary is sometimes reputed to have ordered the first modern [[perfume]] in Europe, called 'Hungary water'.]]
'''Hungary water''' (sometimes called "the Queen of Hungary's Water",<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/012114297|title=A plain introduction to the art of physick, containing the fundamentals, and necessary preliminaries to practice. To which is added, the Materia medica contracted. And alphabetical tables of the vertues of roots, barks, ... Also a collection of choice medicines chymical and Galenical. Together with a different way of making the most celebrated compositions in the apothecaries shops ..|last=Pechey|first=John|last2=Marggraf|first2=Christiaan|last3=Ettmüller|first3=Michael|date=1697|publisher=Henry Bonwicke|year=1697|isbn=|location=London|pages=377–378|access-date=2018-05-26}}</ref> ''Eau de la Reine de Hongary'',<ref name=":0" /> or "spirits of rosemary"<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last=Sullivan|first=Catherine|date=1994-03-01|title=Searching for nineteenth-century Florida water bottles|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/BF03374182|journal=Historical Archaeology|language=en|volume=28|issue=1|pages=78–98|doi=10.1007/BF03374182|issn=0440-9213}}</ref>) was one of the first alcohol-based [[Perfume|perfumes]] in [[Europe]], primarily made with rosemary.<ref name=":0" /> The oldest surviving recipes call for distilling fresh [[rosemary]] and [[thyme]]<ref name=":6">{{Cite book|url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/011609976|title=The lady's receipt-book: a useful companion for large or small families|last=Leslie|first=Eliza|date=1847|publisher=Carey and Hart|year=|isbn=|location=Philadelphia|pages=254}}</ref> with [[brandy]],<ref name=":3">{{Cite book|url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/009291922|title=The toilet of Flora or A collection of the most simple and approved methods of preparing baths, essences, pomatums, powders, perfumes and sweet-scented waters|last=Buc'hoz|first=Pierre-Joseph|last2=Nicoll|first2=William|last3=Murray|first3=John|last4=Montoya y Solís|first4=Fernando|date=1784|publisher=printed for J. Murray ... and W. Nicoll ...|year=|isbn=|location=London|pages=35–37|access-date=2018-05-26}}</ref> while later formulations contain [[wine]],<ref name=":4">{{Cite book|url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/100158274|title=A compleat body of distilling: explaining the mysteries of that science, in a most easy and familiar manner: containing an exact and accurate method of making all the compound cordial-waters now in use: with a particular account of their several virtues: as also a directory consisting of all the instructions necessary for learning the distiller's art ...: in two parts|last=Smith|first=George|date=1731|publisher=Printed for Henry Lintot|year=|isbn=|volume=Book II|location=London|pages=118–121|access-date=2018-05-26}}</ref><ref name=":5">{{Cite book|url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/008596736|title=The British perfumer: being a collection of choice receipts and observations made during an extensive practice of thirty years, by which any lady or gentleman may prepare their own articles of the best quality, whether of perfumery, snuffs, or colours.|last=Lillie|first=Charles.|last2=Mackenzie|first2=Colin, ed.|date=1822|publisher=J. Souter; W. Seaman|year=|isbn=|location=London, New York|pages=142–145|access-date=2018-05-26}}</ref> [[lavender]],<ref name=":4" /><ref name=":5" /> [[Mentha|mint]], [[Salvia officinalis|sage]],<ref name=":6" /> [[marjoram]],<ref name=":3" /> [[Saussurea costus|costus]], [[neroli|orange blossom]] and [[lemon]].
== Origins == The exact date of the invention of Hungary water is lost to history, though some sources say it dates to 1370<ref name=":1" /><ref name=":2">{{Cite book|title=The Mystery and Lure of Perfume|last=Thompson|first=C.J.S.|publisher=John Lane the Bodley Head Limited|year=1927|isbn=|location=London|pages=140}}</ref> or the late 14th century.<ref name=":0" /> It is equally unclear who in particular created it. According to legend, it was formulated at the command of the Queen Elizabeth of Hungary,<ref name=":1">{{Cite journal|last=Voudouri|first=Dimitra|last2=Tesseromatis|first2=Christine|date=December 2015|title=Perfumery from Myth to Antiquity|url=http://ijmpnet.com/journals/ijmp/Vol_3_No_2_Decembe_2015/4.pdf|journal=International Journal of Medicine and Pharmacy|volume=3|issue=2|pages=52|doi=10.15640/ijmp.v3n2a4|via=}}</ref> sometimes identified as Queen Isabella of Hungary{{Citation needed|date=May 2018}}<ref group="note">Historically, the name Isabella was a variant of Elisabeth, and in the period in question the two were sometimes interchangeable.</ref> or in one document{{Specify}} "Saint Elisabeth, Queen of Hungary".<ref group="note">This may be a conflation of multiple individuals.</ref> Some sources say that a hermit or monk-recluse first gave it to the Queen of Hungary,<ref name=":2" /> though most likely it was made by a court alchemist or a monk-alchemist.{{Citation needed|date=May 2018}} These legends mostly date to the early to mid-17th century,{{Citation needed|date=May 2018}} so the details may have become confused in the intervening centuries.
=== Namesake === The queen in question is frequently assumed{{By whom|date=May 2018}} to be [[Elisabeth of Poland]] (1305–1380), although the particulars of her life do not match those in the more common legends. It is even more unlikely that it could be Saint [[Elisabeth of Hungary]] (1207–1231), who is additionally too early and not a queen.<ref group="note">The technique of [[distillation]] only became well known in Europe between about 1150 and 1250.</ref> The only plausible Queen Isabella (late 13th century){{Citation needed|date=May 2018}} likewise seems to be too early to be a strong candidate, as the invention of this water is most probably related{{Why|date=May 2018}} to the [[Black Death]] epidemic that ravaged Europe between 1346 and 1350.
== Spread through Europe == According to legends, Hungary water first appeared outside of [[Hungary]] in 1370 when [[Charles V of France]], who was famous for his love of fragrances, received some.{{Citation needed|date=May 2018}} Its use was popular across Europe for many centuries, and until ''[[Eau de Cologne]]'' appeared in the 18th century, it was the most popular fragrance and remedy applied.{{Cn|date=May 2018}}
=== French Hungary water === By the 18th century, French Hungary water from [[Montpellier]]<ref>{{Citation |publisher = Longman, Hurst, Rees, Orme & Brown |publication-date = 1819 |publication-place = London |title = [[Rees's Cyclopædia|The Cyclopaedia]] |author= Abraham Rees |chapter=Montpelier |chapterurl= https://archive.org/stream/cyclopaediaoruni24rees#page/n51/mode/1up }}</ref> was being touted over other variations of Hungary water, because of the quality of the rosemary used in the distillation.<ref name=":5" /> Advertisements in newspapers even warned against counterfeit versions of French Hungary water, explaining to potential buyers how to detect the difference in quality.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1724-1725|title=The Weekly journal: or, Saturday's post. With freshest advice foreign and domestick.|url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/101820441|journal=|volume=|pages=1619|access-date=2018-05-26|via=}}</ref>
== Usage == Similar to other herb and flower-based products, Hungary water was also a valuable remedy, with recipes advising the user to wash with it<ref name=":4" /> or drink it in order to receive the most benefit.<ref name=":3" /> It was even thought to help people maintain youthful appearance and beauty.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":2" />
