{{italic title}} '''''The Low Road''''' is a 2013 play by the American playwright [[Bruce Norris (playwright)|Bruce Norris]]. It premiered from 23 March to 11 May 2013 at the [[Royal Court Theatre]]<ref name=Taylor>{{cite web|author=Paul Taylor |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/reviews/the-low-road-royal-court-london-8553085.html |title=The Low Road, Royal Court, London - Reviews - Theatre & Dance |publisher=The Independent |date=2013-03-28 |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref> in [[London]], in a production directed by [[Dominic Cooke]] (his final production as Artistic Director of that theatre) and with a cast including [[Bill Paterson (actor)|Bill Paterson]], [[Joe Flynn (UK actor)|Johnny Flynn]], [[Kobna-Holdbrook Smith]], [[Simon Paisley Day]], [[Elizabeth Berrington]], [[Ian Gelder]], [[Ellie Kendrick]] and [[John Ramm]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/theatre-reviews/9959579/The-Low-Road-Royal-Court-review.html |title=The Low Road, Royal Court, review |publisher=Telegraph |date= |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Henry Hitchings |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/goingout/theatre/the-low-road-royal-court-downstairs--theatre-review-8552675.html |title=The Low Road, Royal Court Downstairs - theatre review - Theatre - Going Out - London Evening Standard |publisher=Standard.co.uk |date=2013-03-28 |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref>
The play focuses on the economic theories of [[Adam Smith]], who acts as the narrator, first by showing us an 18th-century story in which Jim Trumpett, a young American of illegitimate birth and raised in a brothel, stumbles upon Smith's ''[[The Wealth of Nations]]'' and becomes a convert to the new theories of capitalism, and then showing us, through a contemporary scene featuring a [[G8 summit]], that our thinking hasn't changed at all. Theater critic Paul Taylor claims that the play was motivated by the [[2008 financial crisis]] and the failure of the banking community to change their behaviors.<ref name=Taylor/>
